Project: Thera Bank Personal Loan Campaign Modelling¶

Data Description:¶

The dataset contains data on 5000 customers. The data include customer demographic information (age, income, etc.), the customer's relationship with the bank (mortgage, securities account, etc.), and the customer response to the last personal loan campaign (Personal Loan). Among these 5000 customers, only 480 (= 9.6%) accepted the personal loan that was offered to them in the earlier campaign.

Domain:¶

Banking

Context:¶

This case is about a bank (Thera Bank) whose management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors). A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio with a minimal budget.

Attribute Information:¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customer's age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in 1000 dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP
  • Family: Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Avg. spending on credit cards per month (in 1000 dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate; 3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in 1000 dollars)
  • Personal Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
  • Securities Account: Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?
  • CD Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
  • Online: Does the customer use internet banking facilities?
  • Credit card: Does the customer use a credit card issued by the bank?

Objective:¶

The classification goal is to predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loans.

#Adding State,City,County columns from zipcode for making zipcode more of a category with lesser number of unique values
search = SearchEngine()

#method to return State&City from ZipCode
def find_city(zipcode):
    city_state = search.by_zipcode(zipcode).post_office_city
    return city_state if city_state else 'unknown' 

#method to return County from ZipCode
def find_county(zipcode):
    county = search.by_zipcode(zipcode).county
    return county if county else 'unknown' 

dsBank['State_City'] = dsBank['ZIP_Code'].apply(find_city)
dsBank['County'] = dsBank['ZIP_Code'].apply(find_county)

Insight:¶

  • Min value of Experience attribute is -3 and there are other negative values as well (-1 and -2), this does not make sense as Experience is number of years of professional experience, this needs to be filled before building model

  • CCAvg and Mortgage has 0's that can happen so no need to fill these values

  • Negative experience values are replaced with zero. Tried taking the median of experience for the age range 23-30, since that is the age range for experience 0 and that gives a less recall, precision values after the model is built. So decided to stick with zero

  • Zip Code field has these values that are not converted to right city/state/county 92717, 9307, 92634, 96651, and hence filled state/city and county for these zip codes with 'unknown'

So we can drop the column before doing Univariate and Bivariate analysis

#function to get confusion matrix in a proper format
def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()
In [82]:

Predicted that the customer is likely to take personal loan and the customer finally ended up taking personal loan

True Negative TN (observed=0,predicted=0) - 1353:

Predicted that the customer is not likely to take personal loan and the customer finally ended up not taking personal loan

False Positive FP (observed=0,predicted=1) - 9:

Predicted that the customer is likely to take personal loan and the customer finally ended up not taking personal loan

False Negative FN (observed=1,predicted=0) - 45:

Predicted that the customer is not likely to take personal loan and the customer finally ended up taking personal loan

Confusion matrix means:¶

True Positive TP (observed=1,predicted=1) - 93:

Predicted that the customer is likely to take personal loan and the customer finally ended up taking personal loan

True Negative TN (observed=0,predicted=0) - 1353:

Predicted that the customer is not likely to take personal loan and the customer finally ended up not taking personal loan

False Positive FP (observed=0,predicted=1) - 9:

Predicted that the customer is likely to take personal loan and the customer finally ended up not taking personal loan

False Negative FN (observed=1,predicted=0) - 45:

Predicted that the customer is not likely to take personal loan and the customer finally ended up taking personal loan

Important Features:¶

Based on the coefficient value, "Education_3", "Education_2", "CD_Account_1", "Family_3" and "Family_4" are the top 5 attributes that influence the model output

"Mortgage" has zero coefficient (shown above),so this feature don't help model in predicting target variable

Important Metric:¶

Here the bank wants to predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loan

The model identifies Education, CD Account and Family size as important features to predict if a customer would take up personal loan

The model has very low False Positive (FP), which means that customers who are likely to take personal loan ended up taking one

False positive also indicates this, the dataset provided had some customers that did not take personal loan, but the model predicts they are likely to take, bank can focus on this group to increase the number of personal loan customers

The model has higher True Negative (TN), which means that most of the bank customers are not likely to take personal loan

This model is built on a small dataset and shows higher values for all performance metrics. This can be run on a larger dataset and if the performance metrics are still good, bank can deploy this model for practical use, as in the bank can predict who is likely to take personal loan based on some of these features identified.
